# Review rules (express-mongoose)

Use these checks when reviewing changes in this repo.

## 1) Routing & controller correctness
- Routes should remain thin and delegate to `controllers/*`.
- Ensure the route method/path matches the intended controller and template.
- For protected routes, confirm `middleware/is-auth.js` is applied.

## 2) Auth/session invariants
- Do not break session structure:
  - `req.session.isLoggedIn` is the auth boolean.
  - `req.session.user` holds the logged-in user document (or at least `_id`).
- If touching login/logout/signup:
  - Login must call `req.session.save(...)` before redirecting.
  - Logout must call `req.session.destroy(...)`.
- If adding new protected features, rely on `req.user` (loaded in `app.js`) and guard routes with `is-auth`.

## 3) CSRF safety
- Any new POST/PUT/DELETE form must include the CSRF hidden input:
  - `<input type="hidden" name="_csrf" value="<%= csrfToken %>">`
- Do not disable CSRF middleware unless you also adjust templates and security expectations.

## 4) Mongoose & data integrity
- Ensure schema changes are backward compatible with existing documents where possible.
- When referencing documents:
  - Use `Schema.Types.ObjectId` + `ref` consistently.
- When mutating models:
  - Confirm you call `.save()` and return the promise (or await it if you refactor).
- `Order` intentionally stores **snapshots** of products (`product: Object`); don’t replace it with only product IDs unless you also update views/controllers accordingly.

## 5) Error handling expectations (current style)
- Current code uses promise chains with `.catch(err => console.log(err))`.
- If you refactor to `async/await`, keep behavior consistent:
  - Surround DB calls with try/catch
  - Return/redirect/render in all branches
- Avoid leaving requests hanging (always `return` after redirects inside promise chains when needed).

## 6) Security & configuration review
- Secrets/credentials must not be committed.
- Mongo connection must come from `process.env.MONGODB_URI`.
- Session secret should ideally come from env (currently hard-coded in `app.js`); if you change it, ensure deployments set it.

## 7) View and locals consistency
- `res.locals.isAuthenticated` and `res.locals.csrfToken` are set in `app.js`.
- Many controllers also pass `isAuthenticated` explicitly; if you remove that, ensure templates still work (or update templates to rely on locals consistently).

## 8) Don’t introduce unused dependencies
- Keep `package.json` aligned with actual usage.
- This repo is Express + Mongoose; don’t add heavy frameworks unless requested.